      "@context": "https://schema.org/",
      "@id": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BioEcoOcean/data-prov/refs/heads/main/jsonFiles/zenodo/w-poszukiwaniu-strategii-na-uwzgl-dnienie-roli-bentosu-w-modelowaniu-obiegu-w-gla-organicznego-13927820.json"
    },
    {
      "@type": "CreativeWork",
      "name": "What are biology and ecosystem Essential Ocean Variables (EOVs) and how can they be used in conservation?",
      "url": "https://zenodo.org/record/13968019",
      "identifier": {
        "@type": "PropertyValue",
        "description": "DOI",
        "propertyID": "https://registry.identifiers.org/registry/doi",
        "url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13968019",
        "value": "10.5281/zenodo.13968019"
      },
      "description": "Imagine if we had some key biology and ecosystem variables that are collected in the same way , and made openly available . Then we would be able to use this comparable data from around the world to advance our understanding of the ocean but also to create products that would be very useful in conservation . For example , distribution maps that could indicate areas in decline but also areas that are recovering or flourishing , or as early warning systems of e.g . invasive species.&nbsp; A global view , in other words adopting a global framework , will also provide insights into similarities among areas to find common solutions and learn from each other .&nbsp; The idea&nbsp; behind the biology and ecosystem Essential Ocean Variables ( EOVs ), is to enable this globally coordinated and comparable approach to observations, data management and delivery of products and services. The EOVs are coordinated by the Global Ocean Observing System, IOC- UNESCO, and everyone is encouraged to take part. We will use the Seagrass cover and composition EOV to illustrate this vision and how collaboration can advance our understanding of the ocean and marine conservation .",
      "datePublished": "2024-10-22",
      "creator": [
        {
          "@type": "Person",
          "name": "Nordlund, Lina Mtwana"
        },
        {
          "@type": "Person",
          "name": "Palacz, Artur P."
        },
        {
          "@type": "Person",
          "name": "Duffy, J. Emmett"
        }
      ],
      "license": {
        "id": "cc-by-4.0"
      },
      "funding": [
        {
          "@type": "MonetaryGrant",
          "name": "BioEcoOcean (Horizon Europe)",
          "identifier": "101136748",
          "funder": {
            "@type": "FundingAgency",
            "name": "European Commission",
            "legalName": "European Commission",
            "url": "https://commission.europa.eu/index_en"
          }
        }
      ],
      "@context": "https://schema.org/",
      "@id": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BioEcoOcean/data-prov/refs/heads/main/jsonFiles/zenodo/what-are-biology-and-ecosystem-essential-ocean-variables-eovs-and-how-can-they-be-used-in-conservation-13968019.json"
    },
    {
      "@type": "CreativeWork",
      "name": "Advancing marine conservation through the Marine Organic Carbon Atlas: addressing metazoan roles in ocean carbon sequestration",
      "url": "https://zenodo.org/record/13967583",
      "identifier": {
        "@type": "PropertyValue",
        "description": "DOI",
        "propertyID": "https://registry.identifiers.org/registry/doi",
        "url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13967583",
        "value": "10.5281/zenodo.13967583"
      },
      "description": "Marine conservation efforts targeting metazoans, including plankton, are crucial for maintaining marine ecosystem functions and services, such as ocean carbon sequestration. Vertical migration and trophic interactions involving metazoans significantly contribute to ocean carbon sequestration, with mesopelagic fishes and zooplankton playing key roles. Proposed expansions in fishing, targeting both mesopelagic fishes and krill, raise concerns about ecosystem impacts. However, gaps in data persist regarding how changes in metazoan abundance and biodiversity will affect carbon sequestration. To address this, we present the concept and early implementation steps of a Marine Organic Carbon Atlas which aims to synthesize data and develop ecosystem models for selected Essential Ocean Variables (EOVs) like phyto- and zooplankton, and fish abundance and diversity. Incorporating habitat-forming variables like seagrass and macroalgae highlights their role in carbon sequestration. The atlas pilot demonstration, tested against modeling and science advisory needs, in particular those of integrated ecosystem assessments, aims to inform science-based conservation decisions, such as regulating emerging fishing of krill and mesopelagic fish to ensure ecosystem health and sustainable harvesting levels.",
      "datePublished": "2024-10-22",
      "creator": [
        {
          "@type": "Person",
          "name": "Palacz, Artur P."
        },
        {
          "@type": "Person",
          "name": "Grigoratou, Maria"
        },
        {
          "@type": "Person",
          "name": "Koski, Marja"
        },
        {
          "@type": "Person",
          "name": "Nordlund, Lina Mtwana"
        },
        {
          "@type": "Person",
          "name": "Visser, Andre"
        }
      ],
      "keywords": [
        "carbon sequestration",
        "blue carbon",
        "Marine Organic Carbon Atlas",
        "krill"
      ],
      "license": {
        "id": "cc-by-4.0"
      },
      "funding": [
        {
          "@type": "MonetaryGrant",
          "name": "BioEcoOcean (Horizon Europe)",
          "identifier": "101136748",
          "funder": {
            "@type": "FundingAgency",
            "name": "European Commission",
            "legalName": "European Commission",
